<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
    ServiceNow Update Set record-definition for the synthetic role assignment
    that grants the scoped role `x_casemgmt_case_agent` to the synthetic demo
    user `x_casemgmt_demo_agent`. This is one of exactly THREE role-assignment
    records in the case-management POC scoped application (the others grant
    the manager and viewer roles to their respective demo personas — see
    sys_user_has_role_x_casemgmt_demo_manager.xml and
    sys_user_has_role_x_casemgmt_demo_viewer.xml in this same directory).

    Persona role activated by this grant (per AAP Section 0.5.6 ACL Matrix):
      Once the Update Set commits, the demo agent user holds the
      x_casemgmt_case_agent role and therefore receives:
        - x_casemgmt_case        Create / Read Assigned only / Write Assigned only / NO Delete
        - x_casemgmt_case_task   Create / Read Assigned only / Write Assigned only / NO Delete
        - x_casemgmt_case_party  Create / Read Assigned only / Write Assigned only / NO Delete
      "Assigned only" is defined per AAP Section 0.5.6 as the disjunction
      `current.assigned_agent == gs.getUserID() OR gs.getUser().isMemberOf(current.assigned_group.toString())`,
      encoded in the condition scripts of the assigned-only ACL records at
      ../../acl/x_casemgmt_case_read_agent_assigned.xml and
      ../../acl/x_casemgmt_case_write_agent_assigned.xml (and their mirror
      records for x_casemgmt_case_task and x_casemgmt_case_party). The first
      clause matches whenever the agent is named directly on the case as
      the assigned_agent; the second clause matches whenever the agent is
      a member of the assigned_group. Per the seed configuration, the demo
      agent is added at runtime as the sole member of
      x_casemgmt_demo_team (../groups/sys_user_group_x_casemgmt_demo_team.xml),
      so the second clause activates whenever a demo case has
      assigned_group = "x_casemgmt_demo_team". Per AAP Section 0.5.5 the
      agent has authority to drive the Open -> In Progress, In Progress ->
      Pending, Pending -> In Progress, and In Progress -> Resolved
      transitions, but the manager-only Resolved -> Closed transition is
      gated separately by validate_closed_transition.xml.

    Validation Gate 3 dependency (AAP Section 0.7.3):
      Per the gate's pass condition "case_agent cannot access unassigned
      cases", the operator impersonates the demo agent to verify that
      access is granted ONLY on cases where one of the two "Assigned only"
      clauses is satisfied (direct assignment via assigned_agent or group
      membership via assigned_group). Without THIS role-assignment record,
      the demo agent holds no scoped role at all — making Gate 3's
      verification inconclusive (a denied read attempt could be due to no
      role grant rather than a properly enforced "Assigned only" ACL
      pattern). This file is therefore central to Gate 3 of the seven-row
      validation framework, and uniquely so: the agent persona is the
      only one of the three whose ACL pattern depends on the union of the
      role grant AND the assignment relation between the user and the
      case row.

    Validation Gate 2 dependency (AAP Section 0.7.3):
      Per the Workflow gate's pass condition, all state transitions MUST
      be enforced for both case types. Most state transitions in the
      Flow Designer subflows (validate_open_transition,
      validate_inprogress_transition, validate_pending_transition,
      validate_resolved_transition) fire OnUpdate on records the caller
      can write — meaning they require the caller to hold either the
      x_casemgmt_case_manager role or the x_casemgmt_case_agent role with
      a satisfied "Assigned only" condition. The demo agent is the
      designated persona for exercising the agent-driven transitions
      (Open -> In Progress, In Progress -> Pending, Pending -> In
      Progress, In Progress -> Resolved) on the cases assigned to them.
      Without this role grant, no demo persona can exercise the
      agent-driven transition path during validation testing, leaving
      the Workflow gate inconclusive for the agent scenario.

    Why this assignment record lives in the SCOPED Update Set even though
    `sys_user_has_role` is a global OOB table:
      The scoped Update Set's deliverable is fully self-contained: the
      reviewer must be able to install the Update Set on a fresh PDI and
      immediately exercise all seven validation gates. The three demo
      personas (manager, agent, viewer) are required by Gate 2 (workflow
      transitions including the agent-driven path), Gate 3 (ACL role-
      based access including the "Assigned only" condition unique to the
      agent), and Gate 6 (dashboard rendering with synthetic data — the
      Agent Workspace dashboard's "My open cases" and "My overdue tasks"
      list widgets target this persona via gs.getUserID() filters).
      Tracking the role-assignment records inside the scoped Update Set
      ensures they import together with the rest of the application; the
      scope binding via <sys_scope> and <sys_package> source attribute
      groups them with the scoped app even though their parent table
      (sys_user_has_role) is global. No global-scope WRITES are
      performed: only INSERTS into sys_user_has_role (a data table) —
      the OOB sys_user_has_role dictionary, ACLs, and form layouts are
      never modified.

    Authoring rules honored (per AAP Sections 0.7.1 / 0.7.2 and the agent
    prompt's eight authoring rules):

      Rule 1 — Synthetic Only:
        <user> resolves to `x_casemgmt_demo_agent` — a fully synthetic
        demo persona created by ../users/sys_user_x_casemgmt_demo_agent.xml
        with the unmistakably non-real first_name "Demo" and last_name
        "Agent" and the synthetic email demo-agent@example.invalid
        (RFC 2606 reserved-TLD). <role> resolves to `x_casemgmt_case_agent`
        — a brand-new scoped role defined by
        ../../roles/sys_user_role_x_casemgmt_case_agent.xml. Both sides of
        this association are unmistakably non-real and live exclusively
        inside the x_casemgmt scope. NO real users (no admin, no system)
        and NO OOB roles (no itil, no snc_internal, no
        personalize_dictionary, no admin) are referenced.

      Rule 2 — Zero Hardcoded sys_id Cross-References:
        - The record's OWN <sys_id> below is THIS record's identity key
          (acceptable per AAP rule). It is a deterministic 32-character
          lowercase hex value (MD5 of the canonical
          "x_casemgmt_demo_agent:x_casemgmt_case_agent" tuple) so the
          Update Set engine resolves the same sys_id on every PDI,
          guaranteeing idempotent re-imports during round-trip
          verification. The same MD5-of-tuple algorithm is used by the
          sibling sys_user_has_role_x_casemgmt_demo_manager.xml and
          sys_user_has_role_x_casemgmt_demo_viewer.xml records for
          consistency.
        - The <user> reference resolves by display_value="x_casemgmt_demo_agent"
          — the Update Set engine looks up sys_user.user_name = "x_casemgmt_demo_agent"
          at apply time. The text-node value is the same lookup key (NOT
          a hardcoded sys_id literal) per the project convention used by
          every ACL <roles> field (e.g.,
          ../../acl/x_casemgmt_case_read_agent_assigned.xml uses
          <roles>x_casemgmt_case_agent</roles> as a name lookup, not a
          sys_id literal).
        - The <role> reference resolves by display_value="x_casemgmt_case_agent"
          — the Update Set engine looks up sys_user_role.name = "x_casemgmt_case_agent"
          at apply time. The text-node value is the same lookup key.
        - The <sys_scope> and <sys_package> fields resolve by
          display_value / source attribute lookup against the scoped
          application's sys_scope record (../../app/sys_scope/x_casemgmt.xml,
          where <source>x_casemgmt</source>). The text-node value
          "x_casemgmt" is the scope's source key — the canonical project
          convention used by every other scoped artifact in the Update
          Set, including the sibling demo manager and viewer
          role-assignment records.

      Rule 3 — Scope Binding:
        <sys_scope> binds this assignment record to the scoped application
        whose source attribute is "x_casemgmt" (defined in
        ../../app/sys_scope/x_casemgmt.xml). The display_value attribute
        is "Case Management" — the human-readable scoped-app name. The
        <sys_package> follows the same pattern with the source attribute
        pointing at the scope source name. Although sys_user_has_role is
        a global OOB table, the SCOPED demo grant is tracked in the
        scoped Update Set so the deliverable is fully self-contained.

      Rule 4 — No Inheritance:
        <inherited>false</inherited> (literal lowercase string "false").
        Group-based role inheritance is NOT used in this POC; this is a
        direct user-to-role grant. If <inherited>true</inherited> were
        used, the platform would interpret this row as derivative of a
        parent group's role grant, which would be inconsistent with the
        canonical pattern. Note that the demo agent IS a member of
        x_casemgmt_demo_team (per ../groups/sys_user_group_x_casemgmt_demo_team.xml,
        where the agent is added at runtime as the sole member), but the
        x_casemgmt_case_agent role is NOT granted to that group — the
        role is granted directly to the user via this record. The group
        membership matters only for the second clause of the "Assigned
        only" condition (gs.getUser().isMemberOf(...)), where the demo
        team's name is used to widen the agent's read/write surface to
        cases whose assigned_group references the demo team. The role
        grant itself is independent of and orthogonal to the group
        membership relationship.

      Rule 5 — Active State:
        <state>active</state> (literal lowercase string "active"). The
        role assignment is effective immediately upon Update Set commit.
        Inactive states (requested, pending, expired) are workflow-
        related and not used in the POC seeding flow.

      Rule 6 — Idempotency Anchor:
        The record's idempotent key is the (user, role) tuple
        ("x_casemgmt_demo_agent", "x_casemgmt_case_agent"). The companion
        seed script ../../scripts/seed_demo_data.js's
        ensureRoleAssignment(DEMO.USERS.AGENT, ROLES.AGENT) helper
        queries by both fields BEFORE inserting; the
        action="INSERT_OR_UPDATE" attribute on the inner
        <sys_user_has_role> element provides the equivalent idempotency
        guarantee at Update Set commit time. These exact display_value
        strings MUST match the corresponding values in
        ../users/sys_user_x_casemgmt_demo_agent.xml (<user_name> =
        "x_casemgmt_demo_agent") and
        ../../roles/sys_user_role_x_casemgmt_case_agent.xml (<name> =
        "x_casemgmt_case_agent") — verified at authoring time.

      Rule 7 — Minimum Field Set:
        ONLY the four content fields required by the agent prompt's
        Mandatory Field Specification are populated: user, role,
        inherited, state. Plus the standard ServiceNow housekeeping
        (sys_class_name, sys_id, sys_scope, sys_package, sys_created_by,
        sys_update_name). All additional sys_user_has_role columns
        (granted_by, u_*, etc.) are auto-defaulted by the platform on
        first import. This keeps the file small, avoids dependencies on
        other global tables (no granted_by reference to another sys_user),
        and makes the record resilient to ServiceNow release-version
        drift across Yokohama / Zurich / Australia.

      Rule 8 — Scoped Update Set XML Conventions:
        Root element: <record_update table="sys_user_has_role">
        Inner element: <sys_user_has_role action="INSERT_OR_UPDATE">
        for idempotent re-import per AAP Section 0.7.1 round-trip-
        verification.
        UTF-8 encoding declared in XML prolog.
        Boolean values lowercase: <inherited>false</inherited>.
        Element ordering: alphabetical (matching the sibling
        sys_user_has_role_x_casemgmt_demo_manager.xml and
        sys_user_has_role_x_casemgmt_demo_viewer.xml records and every
        other XML in the scoped Update Set).

    Cross-dependencies (per AAP Section 0.5.2):

      This grant DEPENDS ON (must be loaded BEFORE this record):
        - ../../app/sys_app/x_casemgmt_case_management.xml (scoped app)
        - ../../app/sys_scope/x_casemgmt.xml (scope record - resolves
          sys_scope and sys_package source="x_casemgmt")
        - ../users/sys_user_x_casemgmt_demo_agent.xml (the demo agent
          user — resolves <user> by user_name lookup)
        - ../../roles/sys_user_role_x_casemgmt_case_agent.xml (the
          scoped role — resolves <role> by name lookup)

      Records that DEPEND ON this grant (loaded AFTER this record):
        - The agent-targeted ACL records at
          ../../acl/x_casemgmt_case_create_agent.xml,
          ../../acl/x_casemgmt_case_read_agent_assigned.xml,
          ../../acl/x_casemgmt_case_write_agent_assigned.xml (plus the
          mirror ACL records for x_casemgmt_case_task and
          x_casemgmt_case_party) — the agent's create + assigned-only
          read/write privileges on all three scoped tables are encoded
          in these ACLs and are activated for the demo agent via this
          grant. The "Assigned only" clause
          gs.getUser().isMemberOf(current.assigned_group.toString())
          works because (a) THIS file grants the agent role to the demo
          agent, and (b) the demo agent is added at runtime as a member
          of x_casemgmt_demo_team — both conditions are required for the
          ACL to evaluate true.
        - The field-level ACL at
          ../../acl/x_casemgmt_case_assigned_agent_field_acl.xml — write
          access to the assigned_agent field is restricted to the
          case_manager role AND to the case_agent who is currently
          assigned. Without this grant, the demo agent could never
          modify the assigned_agent field on any case, breaking the
          self-reassignment scenario.
        - The 7 demo cases at ../cases/x_casemgmt_case_demo_03.xml
          through ../cases/x_casemgmt_case_demo_06.xml and
          ../cases/x_casemgmt_case_demo_08.xml through
          ../cases/x_casemgmt_case_demo_10.xml — these cases use
          assigned_agent = x_casemgmt_demo_agent, and the agent's role
          grant is what enables ACL-based access during impersonation
          tests. Without this grant, all seven cases would fail to
          render for the impersonated agent regardless of the assigned_agent
          relation, masking the actual ACL behavior.
        - The 8 demo tasks at ../tasks/x_casemgmt_case_task_demo_*.xml —
          each task references the demo agent via assigned_to. The
          "All tasks must be closed before resolving this case." gate in
          ../../flows/sub_flows/validate_resolved_transition.xml fires
          when the agent attempts to transition their assigned case
          from In Progress to Resolved; without this grant the agent
          cannot reach that transition path during validation testing.
        - Person-type demo party records at
          ../parties/x_casemgmt_case_party_demo_*.xml — some parties may
          use the demo agent as the `person` reference depending on the
          seed-script's party table layout. Although the person
          reference resolves regardless of role grants, validation tests
          will involve impersonating the agent to read/write the
          parties on cases they are assigned to.
        - The validate_inprogress_transition subflow at
          ../../flows/sub_flows/validate_inprogress_transition.xml —
          when the agent transitions a case Open -> In Progress, this
          subflow validates that the assigned_agent (which the agent
          may have just set to themselves) is a member of the
          assigned_group; THIS role grant is the prerequisite for the
          agent persona to be a recognized scoped principal capable of
          driving the transition.
        - The Agent Workspace dashboard at
          ../../dashboards/pa_dashboards_x_casemgmt_agent_workspace.xml —
          its "My open cases" and "My overdue tasks" list widgets
          filter by assigned_agent = javascript:gs.getUserID() and
          assigned_to = javascript:gs.getUserID() respectively; these
          filters return rows ONLY when the impersonated user has the
          x_casemgmt_case_agent role granted, which is achieved via this
          record.
        - Validation Gate 2 (Workflow) testing — the operator
          impersonates the demo agent to verify the agent-driven
          transition paths (Open -> In Progress, In Progress -> Pending,
          Pending -> In Progress, In Progress -> Resolved) succeed for
          both case types (General Inquiry on cases 03/04/05 and
          Complaint on cases 08/09).
        - Validation Gate 3 (ACLs) testing — the operator impersonates
          the demo agent to verify the "Assigned only" ACL pattern: the
          agent CAN read/write cases 03-06 and 08-10 (where they are
          the assigned_agent) but CANNOT read/write any case where
          neither clause of the "Assigned only" condition is satisfied.

    Source-side semantic reference (read-only, NOT byte-for-byte ported)
    per AAP Sections 0.8.1 and 0.7.1:
      - acm-services/acm-service-users/src/main/java/com/armedia/acm/
        services/users/model/ApplicationRolesConfig.java
        Holds `application.roles` as List<String> bound from external
        configuration via @ListValue("application.roles") and exposes
        MERGE_APPLICATION_ROLES_OP = "application.~roles". Semantic
        reference for ArkCase's role-list configuration model. ArkCase's
        mechanism (config-driven `application.roles` list bound to user
        -> role mappings via RolesPrivilegesService) is replaced in the
        target by this OOB ServiceNow sys_user_has_role join-table row
        authored fresh — there is no field-by-field mapping from
        ArkCase's Java model to sys_user_has_role.
      - acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-admin-plugin/src/main/java/
        com/armedia/acm/plugins/admin/service/RolesPrivilegesService.java
        Central CRUD / normalization service for ArkCase role / privilege
        management. ArkCase normalizes role names by uppercasing,
        replacing whitespace with underscores, replacing periods with
        double-underscores, and prepending ROLE_PREFIX = "ROLE_". The
        ServiceNow target replaces this normalization with the scope-
        prefix convention (x_casemgmt_); the ROLE_ prefix is intentionally
        NOT used. Per AAP Section 0.7.1 ("API-compatibility preservation
        is explicitly NOT required"), the ArkCase role-assignment
        infrastructure (Spring service classes, REST controllers under
        /api/v1/plugin/admin/... and /api/latest/plugin/admin/...) is
        explicitly NOT replicated.

    Validation hooks (per the agent prompt):
      - XML well-formedness check using xmllint in its no-output mode
        returns zero errors.
      - The standard no-PII grep targeting common consumer first-name
        and surname patterns plus consumer-email-domain TLD patterns
        returns zero matches in the actual data fields of this record;
        the synthetic identifiers used here (the demo persona user_name
        and the scoped role name) do not include any PII tokens.
      - The standard no-extra-fields grep targeting the granted_by
        element name and the custom-prefix element name pattern returns
        zero matches; neither the granted_by element nor any custom-
        prefixed element is populated on this record.
      - Cross-reference resolution: the display_value="x_casemgmt_demo_agent"
        value matches the <user_name>x_casemgmt_demo_agent</user_name>
        value in ../users/sys_user_x_casemgmt_demo_agent.xml exactly;
        the display_value="x_casemgmt_case_agent" value matches the
        <name>x_casemgmt_case_agent</name> value in
        ../../roles/sys_user_role_x_casemgmt_case_agent.xml exactly.
      - The concrete scope identifier `casemgmt` is used per AAP convention; the same identifier is used in every cross-reference
        at App Engine Studio creation time, and the Update-Set apply-
        time substitution propagates consistently across all bracketed
        placeholders in this artifact.
-->
<record_update table="sys_user_has_role">
    <sys_user_has_role action="INSERT_OR_UPDATE">
        <inherited>false</inherited>
        <role display_value="x_casemgmt_case_agent">x_casemgmt_case_agent</role>
        <state>active</state>
        <sys_class_name>sys_user_has_role</sys_class_name>
        <sys_created_by>admin</sys_created_by>
        <sys_id>0988a3e374b3a9fee4fd767265fba757</sys_id>
        <sys_package display_value="Case Management" source="x_casemgmt">x_casemgmt</sys_package>
        <sys_scope display_value="Case Management">x_casemgmt</sys_scope>
        <sys_update_name>sys_user_has_role_x_casemgmt_demo_agent</sys_update_name>
        <user display_value="x_casemgmt_demo_agent">x_casemgmt_demo_agent</user>
    </sys_user_has_role>
</record_update>
